# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: annenberg-school-for-communication-at-the-university-of-pennsylvania
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:annenberg-school-for-communication-at-the-university-of-pennsylvania/34th-street-magazine] In 1984, the Daily Pennsylvanian incorporated itself, becoming fully editorially and financially independent of the University of Pennsylvania.
[src:annenberg-school-for-communication-at-the-university-of-pennsylvania/34th-street-magazine] In 2014, the paper reduced its printing frequency, dropping its Friday issue.
[src:annenberg-school-for-communication-at-the-university-of-pennsylvania/34th-street-magazine] After the onset of the COVID-19 pandemic in March of 2020, the DP ceased its print publication for the first time since World War II.
[src:annenberg-school-for-communication-at-the-university-of-pennsylvania/34th-street-magazine] In 2021, the DP announced it would maintain printing the further-reduced printing schedule it adopted during the pandemic.
[src:annenberg-school-for-communication-at-the-university-of-pennsylvania/34th-street-magazine] The Daily Pennsylvanian is published in print weekly on Thursdays and daily online when the university is in session.
[src:annenberg-school-for-communication-at-the-university-of-pennsylvania/34th-street-magazine] The organization consists of an editorial arm, headed by the executive editor, and a business arm, headed by the business manager.
[src:annenberg-school-for-communication-at-the-university-of-pennsylvania/34th-street-magazine] Both the executive editor and the business manager report to the publication's president.
[src:annenberg-school-for-communication-at-the-university-of-pennsylvania/34th-street-magazine] The executive editor oversees *The Daily Pennsylvanian* newspaper, the *34th Street* magazine (which is published in print monthly), and *Under the Button*, along with other production teams.
[src:annenberg-school-for-communication-at-the-university-of-pennsylvania/34th-street-magazine] Each publication is overseen by its own editor-in-chief and has its own staff.
[src:annenberg-school-for-communication-at-the-university-of-pennsylvania/34th-street-magazine] Today the newspaper's budget is funded primarily through the sale of advertising by professional and student staff.
[src:annenberg-school-for-communication-at-the-university-of-pennsylvania/34th-street-magazine] It has received various collegiate journalism awards, including several National Pacemaker Awards from the Associated College Press.
[src:annenberg-school-for-communication-at-the-university-of-pennsylvania/34th-street-magazine] The DP was ranked "the most read" college newspaper by *The Princeton Review* in 1990, 1997,1998, and 2001.
[src:annenberg-school-for-communication-at-the-university-of-pennsylvania/34th-street-magazine] Alumni of *The Daily Pennsylvanian* have gone on to careers in academia, politics, and journalism.
[src:annenberg-school-for-communication-at-the-university-of-pennsylvania/american-journalism-journal] Founded in 1981, the **American Journalism Historians Association** (**AJHA**) seeks to advance education and research in mass communication history.
[src:annenberg-school-for-communication-at-the-university-of-pennsylvania/american-journalism-journal] Through its annual meeting, regional conferences, committees, awards, speakers and publications, members work to raise historical standards and ensure that all scholars and students recognize the vast importance of media history and apply this knowledge to the advancement of society.
[src:annenberg-school-for-communication-at-the-university-of-pennsylvania/american-journalism-journal] The organization sponsors an annual fall meeting.
[src:annenberg-school-for-communication-at-the-university-of-pennsylvania/american-journalism-journal] Approximately 120 historians attend and participate in discussions surrounding teaching and research in media history.
[src:annenberg-school-for-communication-at-the-university-of-pennsylvania/american-journalism-journal] Throughout the meeting, scholars present peer-reviewed research, participate in topical panel discussions and generate ideas for articles and books.
[src:annenberg-school-for-communication-at-the-university-of-pennsylvania/american-journalism-journal] At the annual meeting, scholars also participate vigorously in a silent auction that generates thousands of dollars for graduate student aid.
[src:annenberg-school-for-communication-at-the-university-of-pennsylvania/american-journalism-journal] Media history scholars from across the Southeast gather each February for the annual AJHA Southeast Symposium.
[src:annenberg-school-for-communication-at-the-university-of-pennsylvania/american-journalism-journal] The conference is designed to promote graduate and undergraduate research and provides a scholarly forum for student research presentations and discussions.
[src:annenberg-school-for-communication-at-the-university-of-pennsylvania/american-journalism-journal] The AJHA partners with the History Division of AEJMC to sponsor a spring conference in New York City.
[src:annenberg-school-for-communication-at-the-university-of-pennsylvania/american-journalism-journal] This interdisciplinary gathering accepts submissions in all areas of journalism and communication history from all time periods and welcomes scholars from all academic disciplines and stages of their academic careers.
[src:annenberg-school-for-communication-at-the-university-of-pennsylvania/american-journalism-journal] This AJHA committee works to encourage the study of history in graduate and undergraduate mass communication programs.
[src:annenberg-school-for-communication-at-the-university-of-pennsylvania/american-journalism-journal] The AJHA Speakers Bureau features members who share their expertise and knowledge with the media and local and national organizations.
[src:annenberg-school-for-communication-at-the-university-of-pennsylvania/american-journalism-journal] The diversity of the organization's membership enables its bureau to provide a wealth of educational resources on a wide variety of topics related to mass communication history.
[src:annenberg-school-for-communication-at-the-university-of-pennsylvania/american-journalism-journal] During the annual meeting, the AJHA recognizes exceptional peer-reviewed research papers in several categories: faculty paper, student paper, conference paper, minority paper, and women's interest paper.
[src:annenberg-school-for-communication-at-the-university-of-pennsylvania/american-journalism-journal] A panel of judges also presents an award to the single best article published during the year in American Journalism.
[src:annenberg-school-for-communication-at-the-university-of-pennsylvania/amy-gutmann] In 2018, *Fortune* magazine named Gutmann one of the "World's 50 Greatest Leaders".
[src:annenberg-school-for-communication-at-the-university-of-pennsylvania/amy-gutmann] She previously worked at Princeton as provost and Laurance S.
[src:annenberg-school-for-communication-at-the-university-of-pennsylvania/amy-gutmann] Rockefeller University Professor of Politics.
[src:annenberg-school-for-communication-at-the-university-of-pennsylvania/amy-gutmann] She also founded Princeton's ethics center, the University Center for Human Values.
[src:annenberg-school-for-communication-at-the-university-of-pennsylvania/amy-gutmann] Her published works are in the fields of politics, ethics, education, and philosophy.
[src:annenberg-school-for-communication-at-the-university-of-pennsylvania/amy-gutmann] Amy Gutmann was born on November 19, 1949, in Brooklyn, New York, the only child of Kurt and Beatrice Gutmann.
[src:annenberg-school-for-communication-at-the-university-of-pennsylvania/amy-gutmann] She was raised in Monroe, New York, a small town in the lower Hudson Valley.
[src:annenberg-school-for-communication-at-the-university-of-pennsylvania/amy-gutmann] Her father was the youngest of five children in an Orthodox Jewish family in Feuchtwangen, Germany.
[src:annenberg-school-for-communication-at-the-university-of-pennsylvania/amy-gutmann] He was living near Nuremberg, Germany, when Adolf Hitler ascended to power.
[src:annenberg-school-for-communication-at-the-university-of-pennsylvania/amy-gutmann] He fled Nazi Germany in 1934 as a college student.
[src:annenberg-school-for-communication-at-the-university-of-pennsylvania/amy-gutmann] He brought his entire family, including four siblings, to join him in Bombay, India, where he founded a metal fabricating factory.
[src:annenberg-school-for-communication-at-the-university-of-pennsylvania/amy-gutmann] Kurt Gutmann was still living in India in 1948 when he came to New York City for vacation.
[src:annenberg-school-for-communication-at-the-university-of-pennsylvania/amy-gutmann] While there he attended a benefit at a Manhattan hotel, Essex House, where he met Beatrice, Amy's future mother, and the two were married weeks later.
[src:annenberg-school-for-communication-at-the-university-of-pennsylvania/amy-gutmann] Gutmann graduated from Monroe-Woodbury High School in Monroe, New York.
[src:annenberg-school-for-communication-at-the-university-of-pennsylvania/amy-gutmann] She then entered Radcliffe College of Harvard University in 1967 on a scholarship as a math major with sophomore standing.
[src:annenberg-school-for-communication-at-the-university-of-pennsylvania/amy-gutmann] She was the first in her family to graduate from college.
[src:annenberg-school-for-communication-at-the-university-of-pennsylvania/amy-gutmann] Gutmann taught at Princeton University from 1976 to 2004.
[src:annenberg-school-for-communication-at-the-university-of-pennsylvania/amy-gutmann] In 1990, she became the first Laurance S.
[src:annenberg-school-for-communication-at-the-university-of-pennsylvania/amy-gutmann] Rockefeller University Professor at Princeton and the founding director of its University Center for Human Values.
[src:annenberg-school-for-communication-at-the-university-of-pennsylvania/amy-gutmann] As provost of Princeton University from 2001 to 2004, she oversaw Princeton's plan to expand the undergraduate student body by 10 percent and recruited professor K.
[src:annenberg-school-for-communication-at-the-university-of-pennsylvania/amy-gutmann] In her 2004 inaugural address, Gutmann launched the Penn Compact.
[src:annenberg-school-for-communication-at-the-university-of-pennsylvania/amy-gutmann] In 2017 she renewed and updated her vision with the Penn Compact 2022, recommitting the university to these ideals and outlining the next steps: First, to increase inclusion at the university with increases in faculty and student diversity.
[src:annenberg-school-for-communication-at-the-university-of-pennsylvania/amy-gutmann] Second, to integrate knowledge across academic disciplines with a strong emphasis on innovation: Penn was named No.
[src:annenberg-school-for-communication-at-the-university-of-pennsylvania/amy-gutmann] 4 in Reuters' Top 100 World Innovative Universities in 2017, 2018, and 2019, and the university is consistently helping to facilitate commercialization agreements, ringing in over 650 in 2017 (up from fewer than 50 just a decade prior).
[src:annenberg-school-for-communication-at-the-university-of-pennsylvania/amy-gutmann] Another highlight in innovation is Penn's biomedical research and clinical breakthroughs, approved by the FDA to treat cancer using a patient's own immune system.
[src:annenberg-school-for-communication-at-the-university-of-pennsylvania/amy-gutmann] A third priority through the Compact is to have an impact locally, nationally, and globally to bring the benefits of Penn's research, teaching, and service to individuals and communities at home and around the world.
[src:annenberg-school-for-communication-at-the-university-of-pennsylvania/amy-gutmann] This is recently illustrated by the University's $100 million commitment to the Philadelphia School District to remediate environmental hazards—the largest private contribution to the School District in its history.
[src:annenberg-school-for-communication-at-the-university-of-pennsylvania/amy-gutmann] As president, Gutmann oversaw Penn's largest fundraising campaign ever, Power of Penn, which concluded in 2021 with a total of $5.4 billion and included priorities such as a "Penn First Plus" initiative, targeted to support first-generation, low-income students.
[src:annenberg-school-for-communication-at-the-university-of-pennsylvania/amy-gutmann] She previously led the Making History campaign, launched in 2007, which raised a record $4.3 billion, exceeding its goal by more than $800 million.
[src:annenberg-school-for-communication-at-the-university-of-pennsylvania/amy-gutmann] It achieved its $3.5-billion target 16 months ahead of its December 31, 2012, conclusion.
[src:annenberg-school-for-communication-at-the-university-of-pennsylvania/amy-gutmann] It was an unusually broad-based campaign, attracting gifts from nearly 327,000 donors.
[src:annenberg-school-for-communication-at-the-university-of-pennsylvania/amy-gutmann] Gutmann is the only Penn president to lead two fundraising campaigns, and since 2004 she has helped raise over $10 billion for Penn.
[src:annenberg-school-for-communication-at-the-university-of-pennsylvania/amy-gutmann] Gutmann has been a leading national advocate for financial aid based on the need to promote socioeconomic diversity in higher education.
[src:annenberg-school-for-communication-at-the-university-of-pennsylvania/amy-gutmann] Gutmann made Penn one of the handful of universities in the country that substitute grants for loans for any undergraduate student with financial need.
[src:annenberg-school-for-communication-at-the-university-of-pennsylvania/amy-gutmann] In September 2009, for the first time in Penn's history, all undergraduates eligible for financial aid received grants rather than loans in their aid packages.
[src:annenberg-school-for-communication-at-the-university-of-pennsylvania/amy-gutmann] Students from typical families with income less than $40,000 pay no tuition, fees, room, or board.
[src:annenberg-school-for-communication-at-the-university-of-pennsylvania/amy-gutmann] Students from typical families with incomes less than $90,000 pay no tuition and fees.
[src:annenberg-school-for-communication-at-the-university-of-pennsylvania/amy-gutmann] In 2017, one out of eight incoming Penn students were the first in their families to attend college, up from one out of 20 in 2004.
[src:annenberg-school-for-communication-at-the-university-of-pennsylvania/amy-gutmann] She and her husband Michael Doyle have also funded an endowed undergraduate scholarship and an undergraduate research fund at Penn.
[src:annenberg-school-for-communication-at-the-university-of-pennsylvania/amy-gutmann] In 2017, they committed an additional more than $1 million for scholarships, supporting multiple students and matching funds for other donors.
[src:annenberg-school-for-communication-at-the-university-of-pennsylvania/amy-gutmann] In 2020, Gutmann and Doyle donated $2 million to Penn's nursing school to establish leadership scholarships for undergraduates and graduates who are passionate about making lasting impact in underserved urban and rural communities.
[src:annenberg-school-for-communication-at-the-university-of-pennsylvania/amy-gutmann] In 2014, Gutmann announced Penn Compact 2020 initiatives to create up to 50 new endowed professorships utilizing matching donor funds, and to raise an additional $240 million for undergraduate financial aid on top of the $360 million raised for undergraduate aid during the Making History campaign.
[src:annenberg-school-for-communication-at-the-university-of-pennsylvania/amy-gutmann] Additionally, Gutmann announced unique and unprecedented awards for undergraduate students "with the most promising plans to improve local, national, or global conditions in the year after their graduation".
[src:annenberg-school-for-communication-at-the-university-of-pennsylvania/amy-gutmann] In March 2015, Gutmann announced the selection of five students (four projects) as winners of Penn's inaugural President's Engagement Prize.
[src:annenberg-school-for-communication-at-the-university-of-pennsylvania/amy-gutmann] The largest of their kind in higher education, the President's Engagement Prizes provide up to $150,000 annually for graduating seniors to design and implement impactful local, national, and global engagement projects.
[src:annenberg-school-for-communication-at-the-university-of-pennsylvania/amy-gutmann] Shadrack Frimpong, a 2015 alumnus, used his President's Engagement Prize to start a school for girls, many of whom did not have access to education.
[src:annenberg-school-for-communication-at-the-university-of-pennsylvania/amy-gutmann] Frimpong returned to Penn in 2018 to complete a degree in non-profit leadership and management at Penn to continue his work.
[src:annenberg-school-for-communication-at-the-university-of-pennsylvania/amy-gutmann] Since arriving at Penn, Gutmann has also spearheaded a major campus development plan, Penn Connects, that includes 24 acres (97,000 m2) that Penn purchased from the US Postal Service along the Schuylkill River, which opened as Penn Park in September 2011.
[src:annenberg-school-for-communication-at-the-university-of-pennsylvania/amy-gutmann] Penn Connects is designed to boost the economic, educational and social capacity of Philadelphia and to create seamless gateways between West Philadelphia and Center City across the Schuylkill River.
[src:annenberg-school-for-communication-at-the-university-of-pennsylvania/amy-gutmann] Penn began an expansion east of the Schuylkill River with the purchase of the DuPont Marshall Laboratory in September 2010.
[src:annenberg-school-for-communication-at-the-university-of-pennsylvania/amy-gutmann] Gutmann said that the Marshall Lab property has "infinite possibilities" as a place to nurture startups and "technology transfer", where faculty with "great discoveries can attract venture capital" and bring ideas to market.
[src:annenberg-school-for-communication-at-the-university-of-pennsylvania/amy-gutmann] The $35-million project is about 1 1/2 miles from the center of Penn's West Philadelphia campus.
[src:annenberg-school-for-communication-at-the-university-of-pennsylvania/amy-gutmann] A large, red-letter sign reads "Pennovation" over the three-story, 58,000-square foot facility.
[src:annenberg-school-for-communication-at-the-university-of-pennsylvania/amy-gutmann] Pennovation includes an addition that resembles a crystal formation, representing the "crystallization of ideas", and architecture critic Inga Saffron says that its unique design "announces the future", rather than harkening back to the past.
[src:annenberg-school-for-communication-at-the-university-of-pennsylvania/amy-gutmann] Johnson & Johnson announced in July 2018 that Pennovation Works would house J&J's first US-based JPOD, a networking hub that seeks to connect J&J researchers and the local life sciences community.
[src:annenberg-school-for-communication-at-the-university-of-pennsylvania/amy-gutmann] With the announcement, J&J joined the ranks of global telecom giant Qualcomm and chocolate maker Hershey's, which also selected Pennovation Works to open Philadelphia operations.
[src:annenberg-school-for-communication-at-the-university-of-pennsylvania/amy-gutmann] On December 8, 2014, *The Daily Pennsylvanian* reported that student protesters concerned about the death of Michael Brown in Ferguson, Missouri, disrupted a holiday party for students at Gutmann's home.
[src:annenberg-school-for-communication-at-the-university-of-pennsylvania/amy-gutmann] As a gesture of support for the students' cause, Gutmann joined them in lying on the ground to symbolize the four-and-a-half hours that Brown's body was left lying on the street in Ferguson after his death.
[src:annenberg-school-for-communication-at-the-university-of-pennsylvania/amy-gutmann] Members of the Penn police force publicly responded to the show of support, with the head of the police union writing a public letter criticizing the move and the chief of the police department responding with a letter defending Gutmann's actions.
[src:annenberg-school-for-communication-at-the-university-of-pennsylvania/amy-gutmann] On May 8, 2012, Penn announced that Gutmann's contract had been renewed through 2019.
[src:annenberg-school-for-communication-at-the-university-of-pennsylvania/amy-gutmann] Cohen, chair of Penn's Board of Trustees, stated that Penn's "Trustees feel very strongly that Amy Gutmann is simply the best university president in the country.
[src:annenberg-school-for-communication-at-the-university-of-pennsylvania/amy-gutmann] Under her superb leadership, Penn is a stronger and more vibrant institution than at any time in its storied history." In November 2016 Cohen, still Board Chairman, announced that Gutmann's contract would be extended until 2022, making her the longest-serving president ever at Penn.
[src:annenberg-school-for-communication-at-the-university-of-pennsylvania/amy-gutmann] In 2017, Gutmann's total compensation was $2.9 million, making her the highest paid private college president in Pennsylvania and fourth highest in the United States.
[src:annenberg-school-for-communication-at-the-university-of-pennsylvania/amy-gutmann] Gutmann was also the recipient of a $3.7 million dollar loan from the University of Pennsylvania that remained 100% outstanding as of the end of 2021.
[src:annenberg-school-for-communication-at-the-university-of-pennsylvania/amy-gutmann] On July 2, 2021, President Joe Biden nominated her to serve as the United States Ambassador to Germany.
[src:annenberg-school-for-communication-at-the-university-of-pennsylvania/amy-gutmann] Hearings on her nomination were held before the Senate Foreign Relations Committee on December 14, 2021.
[src:annenberg-school-for-communication-at-the-university-of-pennsylvania/amy-gutmann] Her nomination expired at the end of the year and was returned to President Biden on January 3, 2022.
[src:annenberg-school-for-communication-at-the-university-of-pennsylvania/amy-gutmann] President Biden renominated Gutmann the next day.
[src:annenberg-school-for-communication-at-the-university-of-pennsylvania/amy-gutmann] The committee favorably reported her nomination to the Senate floor on January 12, 2022.
[src:annenberg-school-for-communication-at-the-university-of-pennsylvania/amy-gutmann] On February 8, 2022, the United States Senate confirmed her nomination by a 54-42 vote.
[src:annenberg-school-for-communication-at-the-university-of-pennsylvania/amy-gutmann] She presented her credentials on February 17, 2022.
[src:annenberg-school-for-communication-at-the-university-of-pennsylvania/amy-gutmann] Originating in Feuchtwangen, Gutmann's father, Kurt Gutmann, fled Nazi Germany in 1934 making her mission deeply personal, as well as professional.
[src:annenberg-school-for-communication-at-the-university-of-pennsylvania/amy-gutmann] Among her many priorities and accomplishments as U.S.
[src:annenberg-school-for-communication-at-the-university-of-pennsylvania/amy-gutmann] Ambassador includes her "Stand Up and Speak Out" campaign across Germany to combat intolerance and bias among transatlantic youth.
[src:annenberg-school-for-communication-at-the-university-of-pennsylvania/amy-gutmann] Gutmann resigned her post in July 2024 and returned to the faculty at Penn.
[src:annenberg-school-for-communication-at-the-university-of-pennsylvania/amy-gutmann] Through her writings, Gutmann has sought to bridge theory and policy to advance the core values of a civil democratic society: liberty, opportunity and mutual respect.
[src:annenberg-school-for-communication-at-the-university-of-pennsylvania/amy-gutmann] In a recent ranking of US political scientists in PhD-granting departments, she is ranked second-highest in citations among all political theorists, eighth-highest among all women political scientists, and has been cited more than any other political scientist at the University of Pennsylvania.
[src:annenberg-school-for-communication-at-the-university-of-pennsylvania/amy-gutmann] Her first major contribution to political philosophy was her book *Democratic Education* (1987; revised 1999).
[src:annenberg-school-for-communication-at-the-university-of-pennsylvania/amy-gutmann] The book addresses the central questions in the political theory of education: How should a democratic society make decisions about education?
[src:annenberg-school-for-communication-at-the-university-of-pennsylvania/amy-gutmann] It was reviewed in *Ethics* as "the finest contribution to the literature on democratic education of the last seventy years" and fostered a revival of interest in the relationship between democracy and education.
[src:annenberg-school-for-communication-at-the-university-of-pennsylvania/amy-gutmann] The book also takes on some contemporary scholarly debates: What is the appropriate response of democratic education to the challenge of multiculturalism?
[src:annenberg-school-for-communication-at-the-university-of-pennsylvania/amy-gutmann] Should schools try to cultivate patriotic or cosmopolitan sentiments among students?
[src:annenberg-school-for-communication-at-the-university-of-pennsylvania/amy-gutmann] Gutmann's second major contribution to political philosophy is a theory of deliberative democracy that she developed in collaboration with Harvard political scientist Dennis Thompson.
[src:annenberg-school-for-communication-at-the-university-of-pennsylvania/amy-gutmann] *Democracy and Disagreement* (1996) calls for more reasoned and respectful argument in everyday politics.
[src:annenberg-school-for-communication-at-the-university-of-pennsylvania/amy-gutmann] Deliberation can inform decision making through reasoned argument and develop society's collective capacity to pursue justice while finding mutually acceptable terms of social cooperation—even when disagreements persist.
[src:annenberg-school-for-communication-at-the-university-of-pennsylvania/amy-gutmann] Gutmann's third major contribution to political philosophy is her analysis of group identity and its intersection with justice.
[src:annenberg-school-for-communication-at-the-university-of-pennsylvania/amy-gutmann] In *Identity in Democracy* (2003), Gutmann argues that identity groups as such are neither friends nor enemies of democratic justice.
[src:annenberg-school-for-communication-at-the-university-of-pennsylvania/amy-gutmann] She analyzes the legitimate but also problematic parts played by group identity in democratic politics and draws distinctions among the various types of identity group politics.
[src:annenberg-school-for-communication-at-the-university-of-pennsylvania/amy-gutmann] She further developed this perspective in her nationally recognized 2018 Penn Commencement speech, "Think Uniquely, Stand United", in which she said that ". . . what makes us unique and what unites us are not starkly opposed.
[src:annenberg-school-for-communication-at-the-university-of-pennsylvania/amy-gutmann] Uniqueness and unity are the twin pillars of a strong pluralism.
[src:annenberg-school-for-communication-at-the-university-of-pennsylvania/amy-gutmann] We thrive when we combine unity of shared values with our unique perspectives on life.
[src:annenberg-school-for-communication-at-the-university-of-pennsylvania/amy-gutmann] In May 2012, Gutmann published her 16th book, *The Spirit of Compromise: Why Governing Demands It and Campaigning Undermines It* (Princeton University Press), with co-author Dennis Thompson of Harvard.
[src:annenberg-school-for-communication-at-the-university-of-pennsylvania/amy-gutmann] The authors posit that the difficulty of compromise is built into the democratic process itself, but so is the need for it.
[src:annenberg-school-for-communication-at-the-university-of-pennsylvania/amy-gutmann] A better understanding and appreciation of compromise might be especially useful in this time of political polarization.
[src:annenberg-school-for-communication-at-the-university-of-pennsylvania/amy-gutmann] Judy Woodruff of the PBS Newshour called the book "a clear-eyed examination of the forces that bring warring political leaders together or keep them apart.
[src:annenberg-school-for-communication-at-the-university-of-pennsylvania/amy-gutmann] I wish every policymaker would read it".
[src:annenberg-school-for-communication-at-the-university-of-pennsylvania/amy-gutmann] Gutmann's 17th book, co-authored with Jonathan Moreno, *Everybody Wants to Go to Heaven, but Nobody Wants to Die*, was published in 2019 by W.
[src:annenberg-school-for-communication-at-the-university-of-pennsylvania/amy-gutmann] In 2009, Barack Obama appointed Gutmann chair of the Presidential Commission for the Study of Bioethical Issues, and reappointed her in early 2012, a position she held through 2016.
[src:annenberg-school-for-communication-at-the-university-of-pennsylvania/amy-gutmann] The Bioethics Commission issued 10 reports on a variety of issues including protections for adult and pediatric participants in medical research, and the ethics of genomics and neuroscience.
[src:annenberg-school-for-communication-at-the-university-of-pennsylvania/amy-gutmann] The Commission's meetings were open to the public and streamed live—and all its recommendations to the President were unanimous.
[src:annenberg-school-for-communication-at-the-university-of-pennsylvania/amy-gutmann] Its capstone report, *Bioethics for Every Generation*, focused on the mission of bioethics commissions in advancing democratic deliberation and bioethics education.
[src:annenberg-school-for-communication-at-the-university-of-pennsylvania/amy-gutmann] From 2005 to 2009, Gutmann served on the National Security Higher Education Advisory Board, a committee that advises the FBI on national security issues relating to academia.
[src:annenberg-school-for-communication-at-the-university-of-pennsylvania/amy-gutmann] From 2011 to 2013 she was a member of the National Commission on the Humanities and Social Sciences, which was convened by the American Academy of Arts and Sciences.
[src:annenberg-school-for-communication-at-the-university-of-pennsylvania/amy-gutmann] In 2014, the Association of American Universities elected Gutmann as chair of its board of directors for a one-year term.
[src:annenberg-school-for-communication-at-the-university-of-pennsylvania/amy-gutmann] From 2007 to 2019 Gutmann served on the board of the National Constitution Center in Philadelphia.
[src:annenberg-school-for-communication-at-the-university-of-pennsylvania/amy-gutmann] She was a member of the Knight Commission on Trust, Media and Democracy from 2017 to 2019.
[src:annenberg-school-for-communication-at-the-university-of-pennsylvania/amy-gutmann] From 2006 to 2022, Gutmann served on the board of The Vanguard Group, and was a member of the board of directors of the Berggruen Institute from 2014 to 2022.
[src:annenberg-school-for-communication-at-the-university-of-pennsylvania/amy-gutmann] As of 2009, Gutmann was a member of the Global University Leaders Forum (GULF), which convenes at the World Economic Forum in Davos, Switzerland.
[src:annenberg-school-for-communication-at-the-university-of-pennsylvania/amy-gutmann] Gutmann is married to Michael Doyle, professor of law and international affairs at Columbia University.
[src:annenberg-school-for-communication-at-the-university-of-pennsylvania/amy-gutmann] They have one daughter, Abigail Doyle, a Professor of Chemistry at UCLA where she holds the Saul Winstein Chair in Organic Chemistry.
[src:annenberg-school-for-communication-at-the-university-of-pennsylvania/annenberg-center-for-the-performing-arts] The **Annenberg Center for the Performing Arts** is a theatre, dance and world music venue in Philadelphia, Pennsylvania.
[src:annenberg-school-for-communication-at-the-university-of-pennsylvania/annenberg-center-for-the-performing-arts] It helped to popularize the works of composers like Steve Reich and Philip Glass; the Center has also hosted shows by performers ranging from the Jerusalem Symphony Orchestra to Ladysmith Black Mambazo.
[src:annenberg-school-for-communication-at-the-university-of-pennsylvania/annenberg-center-for-the-performing-arts] The Annenberg facility was designed by Vincent G.
[src:annenberg-school-for-communication-at-the-university-of-pennsylvania/annenberg-center-for-the-performing-arts] Kling who also designed the Philadelphia Mint.
[src:annenberg-school-for-communication-at-the-university-of-pennsylvania/annenberg-center-for-the-performing-arts] The Annenberg Center, founded in 1971, is a major cultural destination and crossroads in the performing arts, connecting Philadelphia regional audiences and the University of Pennsylvania through exposure to innovative human expression in theatre, music, and dance.
[src:annenberg-school-for-communication-at-the-university-of-pennsylvania/annenberg-center-for-the-performing-arts] The Annenberg Center highlights the value of the performing arts by presenting world-renowned and emerging artists and companies who express adventuresome perspectives on contemporary issues, timeless ideas, and diverse cultures.
[src:annenberg-school-for-communication-at-the-university-of-pennsylvania/annenberg-center-for-the-performing-arts] By offering contextualization programs, featuring Penn faculty as well as experts from the artistic and business communities, the Annenberg Center promotes critical thinking among its audiences, creating uniquely rewarding arts experiences.
[src:annenberg-school-for-communication-at-the-university-of-pennsylvania/annenberg-foundation] The **Annenberg Foundation** is an American foundation that provides funding and support to non-profit organizations.
[src:annenberg-school-for-communication-at-the-university-of-pennsylvania/annenberg-foundation] The Annenberg Foundation was established by Walter H.
[src:annenberg-school-for-communication-at-the-university-of-pennsylvania/annenberg-foundation] Annenberg in 1989 with $1.2 billion, one-third of the assets from the sale of Annenberg's Triangle Publications.
[src:annenberg-school-for-communication-at-the-university-of-pennsylvania/annenberg-foundation] The Annenberg Foundation is a grantmaking institution that has provided money towards educational programming, environmental stewardship, social justice, and animal welfare.
[src:annenberg-school-for-communication-at-the-university-of-pennsylvania/annenberg-foundation] As of 2021, the foundation has $1.59 billion in assets.
[src:annenberg-school-for-communication-at-the-university-of-pennsylvania/annenberg-foundation] Annenberg headed the Annenberg Foundation until his death in 2002.
[src:annenberg-school-for-communication-at-the-university-of-pennsylvania/annenberg-foundation] Leonore Annenberg, his wife, ran it until her death in March 2009.
[src:annenberg-school-for-communication-at-the-university-of-pennsylvania/annenberg-foundation] Since then, the foundation's trusteeship was led by Walter's daughter Wallis Annenberg and three of her children: Lauren Bon, Gregory Annenberg Weingarten, and Charles Annenberg Weingarten.
[src:annenberg-school-for-communication-at-the-university-of-pennsylvania/annenberg-foundation] However, on December 2, the Foundation announced that it was suspending its plans.
[src:annenberg-school-for-communication-at-the-university-of-pennsylvania/annenberg-foundation] The *Los Angeles Times* reported that some wetlands advocates had opposed the proposal.
[src:annenberg-school-for-communication-at-the-university-of-pennsylvania/annenberg-foundation] The *Los Angeles Daily News* noted that this was the Foundation's second failed attempt to construct this project on public land.
[src:annenberg-school-for-communication-at-the-university-of-pennsylvania/annenberg-foundation] The *Los Angeles Times* and *Los Angeles Daily News* editorial boards called the project "a bad fit" and "inappropriate," respectively.
[src:annenberg-school-for-communication-at-the-university-of-pennsylvania/annenberg-public-policy-center] The **Annenberg Public Policy Center** (**APPC**) is a center for the study of public policy at the Annenberg School for Communication at the University of Pennsylvania.
[src:annenberg-school-for-communication-at-the-university-of-pennsylvania/annenberg-public-policy-center] It is based in West Philadelphia on the campus of the University of Pennsylvania.
[src:annenberg-school-for-communication-at-the-university-of-pennsylvania/annenberg-public-policy-center] The Annenberg Center is a research center.
[src:annenberg-school-for-communication-at-the-university-of-pennsylvania/annenberg-public-policy-center] The Annenberg Center conducts research, convenes panels of experts, hosts lectures and conferences, and publishes reports on five main areas: Political communication, information and society, media and children, health communication, and adolescent risk.
[src:annenberg-school-for-communication-at-the-university-of-pennsylvania/annenberg-public-policy-center] Among the center’s projects are the fact-checking website FactCheck.org, co-founded by APPC’s founding director, Kathleen Hall Jamieson and Brooks Jackson in 2003, and Annenberg Classroom, which provides free resources for teaching about the U.S.
[src:annenberg-school-for-communication-at-the-university-of-pennsylvania/annenberg-public-policy-center] The center also is a founder and coordinator of the Civics Renewal Network, a consortium of more than 40 nonpartisan civics organizations.
[src:annenberg-school-for-communication-at-the-university-of-pennsylvania/annenberg-public-policy-center] The APPC was established in 1993 by Walter and Leonore Annenberg and its ongoing funding comes from an endowment established for it at that time by the Annenberg Foundation.
[src:annenberg-school-for-communication-at-the-university-of-pennsylvania/annenberg-public-policy-center] In 2026, it had around 50 people, including staff, researchers, and postdoctoral fellows.
[src:annenberg-school-for-communication-at-the-university-of-pennsylvania/annenberg-public-policy-center] Architect Fumihiko Maki designed the Center's facilities.
[src:annenberg-school-for-communication-at-the-university-of-pennsylvania/annenberg-school-for-communication-at-the-university-of-pennsylvania] The **Annenberg School for Communication** is the communication school at the University of Pennsylvania.
[src:annenberg-school-for-communication-at-the-university-of-pennsylvania/annenberg-school-for-communication-at-the-university-of-pennsylvania] The school was established in 1958 by Wharton School alumnus Walter Annenberg as the Annenberg School of Communications.
[src:annenberg-school-for-communication-at-the-university-of-pennsylvania/annenberg-school-for-communication-at-the-university-of-pennsylvania] The name was changed to its current title in 1990.
[src:annenberg-school-for-communication-at-the-university-of-pennsylvania/annenberg-school-for-communication-at-the-university-of-pennsylvania] Walter Annenberg founded the Annenberg School of Communication at the University of Pennsylvania in 1958.
[src:annenberg-school-for-communication-at-the-university-of-pennsylvania/annenberg-school-for-communication-at-the-university-of-pennsylvania] The school, whose first class began in 1959, was initially a master's-only program.
[src:annenberg-school-for-communication-at-the-university-of-pennsylvania/annenberg-school-for-communication-at-the-university-of-pennsylvania] The first Annenberg students were admitted in the Fall semester of 1959 and graduated in the Spring semester of 1960.
[src:annenberg-school-for-communication-at-the-university-of-pennsylvania/annenberg-school-for-communication-at-the-university-of-pennsylvania] Gilbert Seldes was the first dean at the school, serving from 1959 until 1963.
[src:annenberg-school-for-communication-at-the-university-of-pennsylvania/annenberg-school-for-communication-at-the-university-of-pennsylvania] George Gerbner, an advisor to communications commissions and a major contributor to cultivation theory, became dean in 1964.
[src:annenberg-school-for-communication-at-the-university-of-pennsylvania/annenberg-school-for-communication-at-the-university-of-pennsylvania] He founded the Cultural Indicators Project in 1967, measuring trends in television content and how it shaped perceptions of society.
[src:annenberg-school-for-communication-at-the-university-of-pennsylvania/annenberg-school-for-communication-at-the-university-of-pennsylvania] The Annenberg School launched its doctoral program in 1968.
[src:annenberg-school-for-communication-at-the-university-of-pennsylvania/annenberg-school-for-communication-at-the-university-of-pennsylvania] The school retained ownership of the *Journal of Communication* from 1974 to 1991, which was published by Penn while Gerbner was editor.
[src:annenberg-school-for-communication-at-the-university-of-pennsylvania/annenberg-school-for-communication-at-the-university-of-pennsylvania] Dean George Gerbner held the post until 1989.
[src:annenberg-school-for-communication-at-the-university-of-pennsylvania/annenberg-school-for-communication-at-the-university-of-pennsylvania] Kathleen Hall Jamieson was dean from 1989 to 2003.
[src:annenberg-school-for-communication-at-the-university-of-pennsylvania/annenberg-school-for-communication-at-the-university-of-pennsylvania] In 1989, the Annenberg School and Oxford University Press published the four-volume *International Encyclopedia of Communications*, the first broad-based attempt to survey the entire communication field.
[src:annenberg-school-for-communication-at-the-university-of-pennsylvania/annenberg-school-for-communication-at-the-university-of-pennsylvania] In 1990, the school changed its name to **Annenberg School for Communication**.
[src:annenberg-school-for-communication-at-the-university-of-pennsylvania/annenberg-school-for-communication-at-the-university-of-pennsylvania] During Jamieson's deanship, the school received two large endowments from the Annenberg Foundation.
[src:annenberg-school-for-communication-at-the-university-of-pennsylvania/annenberg-school-for-communication-at-the-university-of-pennsylvania] In 1993, Walter and Leonore Annenberg, through their foundation, granted Penn $120 million to endow the school and establish the Annenberg Public Policy Center.
[src:annenberg-school-for-communication-at-the-university-of-pennsylvania/annenberg-school-for-communication-at-the-university-of-pennsylvania] In 2002, the Annenberg Foundation gave $100 million to the school for scholarships, faculty chairs, and classroom refurbishment.
[src:annenberg-school-for-communication-at-the-university-of-pennsylvania/annenberg-school-for-communication-at-the-university-of-pennsylvania] Also during this time, the Annenberg School ended its master's program, with prospective students only being able to apply to their doctoral program.
[src:annenberg-school-for-communication-at-the-university-of-pennsylvania/annenberg-school-for-communication-at-the-university-of-pennsylvania] After Jamieson stepped down as dean in 2003, the school named Michael X.
[src:annenberg-school-for-communication-at-the-university-of-pennsylvania/annenberg-school-for-communication-at-the-university-of-pennsylvania] Delli Carpini's term was extended until 2018.
[src:annenberg-school-for-communication-at-the-university-of-pennsylvania/annenberg-school-for-communication-at-the-university-of-pennsylvania] In 2019, John Jackson became the new dean at Annenberg.
[src:annenberg-school-for-communication-at-the-university-of-pennsylvania/annenberg-school-for-communication-at-the-university-of-pennsylvania] In 2024, while in office, President Joe Biden expressed his desire to return to the Penn Biden Center for Diplomacy and Global Engagement after leaving the White House.
[src:annenberg-school-for-communication-at-the-university-of-pennsylvania/annenberg-school-for-communication-at-the-university-of-pennsylvania] Annenberg School offers a five-year doctoral program.
[src:annenberg-school-for-communication-at-the-university-of-pennsylvania/annenberg-school-for-communication-at-the-university-of-pennsylvania] Annenberg also offers a joint doctoral degree in communication and political science.
[src:annenberg-school-for-communication-at-the-university-of-pennsylvania/annenberg-school-for-communication-at-the-university-of-pennsylvania] The school hosts postdoctoral fellowships and visiting scholars.
[src:annenberg-school-for-communication-at-the-university-of-pennsylvania/athletic-nickname] The **athletic nickname**, or equivalently **athletic moniker**, of a university or college within the United States and Canada is the name officially adopted by that institution for at least the members of its athletic teams.
[src:annenberg-school-for-communication-at-the-university-of-pennsylvania/athletic-nickname] This practice at the university and college tertiary higher-education level has proven so popular that it extended to the high school secondary-education level in the United States and Canada and even to the primary-education level as well.
[src:annenberg-school-for-communication-at-the-university-of-pennsylvania/athletic-nickname] In the United States and Canada, multiple recurring themes have appeared over time for choosing a school's athletic nickname.
[src:annenberg-school-for-communication-at-the-university-of-pennsylvania/athletic-nickname] In almost all cases, the institution chooses an athletic nickname with an overtly positive goal in mind, where that goal reflects the character of the institution—either a previously established characteristic or a characteristic hoped for as a goal henceforth.
[src:annenberg-school-for-communication-at-the-university-of-pennsylvania/athletic-nickname] Often by choosing an abstract concept as its athletic moniker, the institution wants to inspire its student-athletes on and off the field to achieve success that the abstract concept represents.
[src:annenberg-school-for-communication-at-the-university-of-pennsylvania/athletic-nickname] Examples: Cornell Big Red, Stanford Cardinal, UIC Flames, Tulane Green Wave.
[src:annenberg-school-for-communication-at-the-university-of-pennsylvania/athletic-nickname] Often by choosing an animal, the school wants to emphasize the instillation of fear of losing athletic competitions to the institution's teams, such as through an especially fierce or stealthy animal.
[src:annenberg-school-for-communication-at-the-university-of-pennsylvania/athletic-nickname] Examples: Michigan Wolverines, Oregon Ducks, Princeton Tigers, Iowa Hawkeyes, California Golden Bears, Minnesota Golden Gophers, Texas Longhorns and the Bowling Green Falcons.
[src:annenberg-school-for-communication-at-the-university-of-pennsylvania/athletic-nickname] Often by choosing a collection that represents a summary of the institution's students or of its history.
[src:annenberg-school-for-communication-at-the-university-of-pennsylvania/athletic-nickname] Such a collection may refer to an ethnicity; a profession; religious designation, such as saints; or other groupings of people.
[src:annenberg-school-for-communication-at-the-university-of-pennsylvania/athletic-nickname] A portion of athletic monikers that fall into this collection category started originally as derogatory epithets from others, but as an act of defiance, the school embraced the term as a rallying cry to overcome the term's negative origin.
[src:annenberg-school-for-communication-at-the-university-of-pennsylvania/athletic-nickname] Because a collection is hard to represent or iconify, when a school chooses a collection as its athletic nickname, the school typically chooses a related but different mascot that symbolizes that collection.
[src:annenberg-school-for-communication-at-the-university-of-pennsylvania/athletic-nickname] A small number of schools choose an archetypical heroic person as their official athletic nickname.
[src:annenberg-school-for-communication-at-the-university-of-pennsylvania/athletic-nickname] This person may be a graduate of the school who is viewed as embodying the school's mission or an archetypal person who is symbolic of the school's area, such as the West Virginia University Mountaineer.
[src:annenberg-school-for-communication-at-the-university-of-pennsylvania/athletic-nickname] In religiously affiliated schools, this person may be an historical person who has received an official designation in that religion, such as a saint in the Roman Catholic or Eastern Orthodox Churches.
[src:annenberg-school-for-communication-at-the-university-of-pennsylvania/athletic-nickname] Likenesses to Native Americans were at one time widely popular athletic monikers, especially for schools that adopted them in the 19th or early 20th century.
[src:annenberg-school-for-communication-at-the-university-of-pennsylvania/athletic-nickname] In recent years, some Native American organizations have protested the unlicensed use of likenesses of Native Americans related to team names, team logos, athletic monikers, cheerleaders, and cheering techniques.
[src:annenberg-school-for-communication-at-the-university-of-pennsylvania/athletic-nickname] The granting of overtly expressed written licenses by Native American organizations to use likenesses of Native Americans in these ways is rare, although not unheard of.
[src:annenberg-school-for-communication-at-the-university-of-pennsylvania/athletic-nickname] In one notable example, two major groups of the Seminole nation, the Seminole Tribe of Florida and Seminole Nation of Oklahoma, have expressly given Florida State University permission to use the nickname "Seminoles" and certain Seminole imagery.
[src:annenberg-school-for-communication-at-the-university-of-pennsylvania/athletic-nickname] Central Michigan University has a similar arrangement with the Saginaw Chippewa Indian Tribe to use the name "Chippewas".
[src:annenberg-school-for-communication-at-the-university-of-pennsylvania/athletic-nickname] Still other schools have embarked on a series of failed attempts to find a replacement.
[src:annenberg-school-for-communication-at-the-university-of-pennsylvania/athletic-nickname] Often, certain nicknames (animals and some abstract concepts, such as Giants, Broncos, or Wildcats) have become very common.
[src:annenberg-school-for-communication-at-the-university-of-pennsylvania/athletic-nickname] However, some nicknames are unique to that school/team such as Illini, Demon Deacons or Fords.
